To model interaction of our LC colloidal motors with light, we assume infinitely strong (fixed) surface boundary conditions at the confining substrates of the LC cell. The free energy potential describing the generally soft surface boundary conditions at the LC-platelet interfaces is dependent on light’s intensity I and its polarization state and can be expressed as14Fplatelet=σI,e∕2∫Pp⋅np2dS,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$F_{{\rm platelet}} = \left[ {\sigma\left( {I,e} \right)/2} \right]{\int} {\left( {{\bf{P}}_{\mathrm{p}} \cdot {\bf{n}}_{\mathrm{p}}} \right)^2\mathrm{d}S,}$$\end{document}where σ(I, e) is the surface anchoring coefficient (an anisotropic part of surface tension) and np defines the orientation of n(r) at the platelet’s surface. This free energy term is always minimized when Pp ⊥ np, as defined by the response of azobenzene-containing monolayers, but the strength of such coupling through light-directed boundary conditions depends on both intensity and polarization state of light traversing the platelet, as determined by σ(I, e). When polarization state changes so that the long axis of ellipse PP rotates, this prompts rotation of nP and rotation of both the platelet and n(r) in the LC bulk, though slipping occurs at large e and low I due to weak coupling defined by the ensuing small σ(I, e). The rotation-driven n(r) distortions in the LC bulk are resisted by the elastic free energy describing the energetic cost of these distortions at fixed boundary conditions at the cell’s confining substrates15Felastic=∫K112∇⋅n2+K222n⋅∇×n2+K332n×∇×n2-K24∇⋅n∇⋅n+n×∇×ndV,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$F_{{\rm elastic}} = {\int} {\left\{ {\begin{array}{*{20}{c}} {\frac{{K_{11}}}{2}\left( {\nabla \cdot {\bf{n}}} \right)^2 + \frac{{K_{22}}}{2}\left[ {{\bf{n}} \cdot \left( {\nabla \times {\bf{n}}} \right)} \right]^2 + \frac{{K_{33}}}{2}\left[ {{\bf{n}} \times \left( {\nabla \times {\bf{n}}} \right)} \right]^2} \\ { - K_{24}\left[ {\nabla \cdot \left[ {{\bf{n}}\left( {\nabla \cdot {\bf{n}}} \right) + {\bf{n}} \times \left( {\nabla \times {\bf{n}}} \right)} \right]} \right]} \end{array}} \right\}\mathrm{d}V},$$\end{document}where K11, K22, K33, and K24 are Frank elastic constants for splay, twist, bend and saddle splay director deformations, respectively. The competition of corresponding light-dependent surface anchoring free energy term and bulk elastic free energy defines conditions for slipping of n(r) at the platelet-LC interfaces, which, in turn, defines the dynamics of our system.
